Q2. 

Person p1 = new Person(1, "A", 30);
Map<Person, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

map.put(p1, 10);

// mutation
p1.setSalary(50);

map.get(p1);

What happens when we mutate the key?
HashMap may fail to retrieve the key because the hashCode changes, causing it to look in the wrong bucket.
Mutating a key can lead to duplicate entries and memory leaks because the same object may exist in multiple buckets.

If equals() returns true but hashCode() differs, HashMap may store duplicate keys in different buckets, breaking correctness.

Custom Sorting: How do you sort a list of Person objects in descending order by name, and if names are equal, in ascending order by salary? Discuss the choice between Comparable and Comparator.
//Comparable defines natural ordering inside the class, while Comparator provides external, flexible sorting logic and allows multiple sorting strategies.
List<Person> person = persons.stream()
                        .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Person::getName,Comparator.reverseOrder()))
                        .thenComparing(Person::getSalary)
                        .collect(Collectors.toList())

// Name → ascending
// Null names → should come last
// Salary → descending (if names equal)            

